04067nam a22006855i 9780231535205DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013000567  a(OCoLC)979967704  a97802315352057 a10.7312/stei163542doi  a(DE-B1597)459356  a(OCoLC)849928855  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBL473b.S76 2013 4aBL473b.S76 2015 7aREL0510002bisacsh04a2112231 aSteinberger, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Problem with God :bWhy Atheists, True Believers, and Even Agnostics Must All Be Wrong /cPeter Steinberger. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. The Problem with God -- t2. What in God’s Name Am I Doing? -- t3. The Impossible Dream -- t4. Even If the Flesh Is Willing -- t5. Atheism . . . -- t6. . . . and Agnosticism -- t7. Full Faith and No Credit -- t8. It’s All in a Good Cause -- t9. Detective Fiction -- t10. An Inkling of . . . -- t11. . . . the Truth -- tAfterword: Not Enough? -- tAmplifications and Clarifications -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex of Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhether people praise, worship, criticize, or reject God, they all presuppose at least a rough notion of what it means to talk about God. Turning the certainty of this assumption on its head, a respected educator and humanist shows that when we talk about God, we are in fact talking about nothing at all—there is literally no such idea—and so all of the arguments we hear from atheists, true believers, and agnostics are and will always be empty and self-defeating.Peter J. Steinberger's commonsense account is by no means disheartening or upsetting, leaving readers without anything meaningful to hold on to. To the contrary, he demonstrates how impossible it is for the common world of ordinary experience to be all there is. With patience, clarity, and good humor, Steinberger helps readers think critically and constructively about various presuppositions and modes of being in the world. By coming to grips with our own deep-seated beliefs, we can understand how traditional ways asserting, denying, or even just wondering about God's existence prevent us from seeing the truth—which, it turns out, is far more interesting and encouraging than anyone would have thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aGod. 7aRELIGION / Philosophy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/stei1635440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231535205423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231535205/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK